                "name": "Trudi Ziga",
                "href": "/profile/Trudi-Ziga"
            },
            "answer_text": "The answer to this question is quite difficult. The use of calculators for elementary school students should be restricted; students rely on the calculator rather than themselves; once students are studying algebra, calculators could be used AFTER the paper and pencil methods are mastered. Basically when working on math w/o a calculator , a student is mentally engaged in the step by step process ; when using a calculator students use steps to get to the end often w/o knowing the reasons why . To solve more advanced math topics the calculator can be an excellent tool . It supplements mental activity; it should not replace it. Math students need to develop good deductive reasoning, critical thinking and problem solving skills with reliance on themselves. Human beings learn very quickly that calculators are a fast way to get things done. If we want to grow more solidly mathematically successful math persons the foundation must be based on solid self-reliance , rather than a tool that does things for you quickly. As for accuracy , that's another story. ",
