            "author_info": {
                "name": "Karen Wootton",
                "href": "/profile/Karen-Wootton"
            },
            "answer_text": "They should. Teachers need to spend time building number sense and flexibility so that students do not rely on calculators, but there is no reason to ban calculators. I\u2019m pretty good at math, yet I will walk through my house in search of a working calculator rather than do a long division problem! Yes, I can do the division on my phone, but I don\u2019t always have my phone right next to me. But that is the point: why have students doing the work their phones will do? I grew up in a time where weeks were spent on how to calculate a square root by hand. I had no idea of WHY I would want to or have any senses of a square root being the length of the side of a square, but I got good at calculating the square root by hand, out to many decimal places. NOBODY calculates a square root by hand anymore! (I\u2019m not talking about square roots of perfect squares, folks!) Teachers need to conduct Number Talks regularly and build students\u2019 capacity for flexibility with numbers. And, teachers need to stop asking questions that can be answered by the student\u2019s phone. Let\u2019s develop students problem solving abilities and get them to think critically and creatively. Leave the mundane stuff to the calculator. ",
