            },
            "answer_text": "Depends on the exam It is worth having calculator and non-calculator papers in a qualification, to test different skills. e.g. basic arithmetic and estimation, algebra, indefinite integrals in a non-calculator paper; trigonometry, logs, definite integrals in a calculator allowed paper (as appropriate to the level). This approach has / is used in UK testing. Or set papers where a calculator is no use to you whatsoever - my friend did her Maths degree at Oxford. That\u2019s 3 years of full-time maths where there is nothing to calculate. Completely different set of skills. You could take in the best scientific calculator, a computer, the internet, mathematica into some of those papers and it would not help ",
