        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Steven Farris",
                "href": "/profile/Steven-Farris"
            },
            "answer_text": "I asked my calculator if it knew the answer to this question, and it replied it did not understand the question? ;) Just kidding. Look, it is simple. Solve the equation x^2 - 3x + 2 = 0. (Here x^2 of course represents x \u201csquared\u201d). You can put this into a graphing calculator, and find the answer. But, as quadratics go, it is relatively simple to solve by hand. And there are many such equations for which finding the solution can be performed by hand. In addition to knowing *how* to do this, and many other relatively straight forward math problems that require some actual *understanding*, it helps to be able to think through things like this mentally without a calculator. And that is what reqiures development. Not using a calculator actually helps to exercise that skill and develop. Once developed, knock yourself out with a calculator. ",
